{"subsystem": "qpdf ASCII85 stream-decode pipeline. Pl_ASCII85Decoder is a qpdf 'Pipeline' filter that decodes the ASCII base-85 (ASCII85 / '<~ ... ~>') encoding used in PDF stream objects. flush() takes the up-to-5 base-85 digit characters accumulated in the object's internal inbuf[], converts a group of 5 base-85 digits back into a 32-bit value, splits it into up to 4 output bytes, and forwards the decoded bytes to the next pipeline stage via getNext()->write(). It runs while parsing untrusted PDF content streams / stream data.", "provenance": "Identified as qpdf by strong naming conventions: the 'Pl_' class-name prefix is qpdf's convention for Pipeline subclasses, 'Pl_ASCII85Decoder' is a qpdf pipeline class, and QTC::TC("libtests", ...) is qpdf's QUtil 'test coverage' instrumentation macro (scope string "libtests"). The sample banner 'primevul_validation_0391_fixed' plus the CWE-787 filename tag indicate this is the post-fix revision of a PrimeVul out-of-bounds-write sample. No SPDX or copyright header is present in the excerpt; qpdf is authored by Jay Berkenbilt and licensed Apache-2.0.", "trust_boundary": "The bytes in this->inbuf[] originate from an attacker-controllable PDF file: a PDF stream's ASCII85-encoded data is fed byte-by-byte into Pl_ASCII85Decoder::write() (not shown), which validates/collects base-85 digit characters into inbuf[] and advances this->pos, calling flush() when a group completes or at end-of-stream. Therefore inbuf[] contents, and critically the value of this->pos, are functions of hostile input. inbuf[] is a small fixed-size member (5 bytes in qpdf) and pos is the count of valid digits; the memory safety of this flush() depends entirely on the invariant 1 <= pos <= 5 being upheld by the not-shown append path.", "what_the_code_does": [{"file": "corpus/train/train_0225_cwe787.cpp", "lines": "2-3", "code": "Pl_ASCII85Decoder::flush()
{", "explanation": "Definition of the flush() member of Pl_ASCII85Decoder. flush() has no parameters and no return value; it operates entirely on member state (this->pos, this->inbuf) and on the downstream pipeline reachable via getNext(). It is the routine that converts one buffered group of ASCII85 digit characters into raw output bytes and emits them. It is invoked both when a full group of 5 digits has been collected and at end-of-stream to drain a partial (2-4 digit) group."}, {"file": "corpus/train/train_0225_cwe787.cpp", "lines": "4-8", "code": "    if (this->pos == 0)
    {
	QTC::TC("libtests", "Pl_ASCII85Decoder no-op flush");
	return;
    }", "explanation": "Early-out guard: if pos is 0 there are no buffered digits, so flush is a no-op and returns immediately. The QTC::TC() call is qpdf's test-coverage hook that records that this no-op branch was exercised (it has no runtime security effect). Crucially, this guard establishes that on every path past this point pos >= 1, which is what makes the later subtraction this->pos - 1 non-negative."}, {"file": "corpus/train/train_0225_cwe787.cpp", "lines": "9-14", "code": "    unsigned long lval = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < 5; ++i)
    {
	lval *= 85;
	lval += (this->inbuf[i] - 33U);
    }", "explanation": "The base-85 accumulation. lval is a 32/64-bit unsigned accumulator initialised to 0. The loop always iterates i = 0..4 (all 5 slots of inbuf), regardless of how many digits were actually collected (this->pos). For each digit it does the standard positional base-85 conversion lval = lval*85 + digit, where the digit value is inbuf[i] - 33 ('!' == 33 is base-85 digit 0, 'u' == 117 is digit 84). The 33U literal is unsigned, so the subtraction is unsigned arithmetic. Because the loop reads all 5 slots even for a partial group, the not-shown code path must have padded the unused high-order slots with the maximum digit 'u' (117); the reset on line 30 (memset(inbuf, 117, 5)) is exactly this padding being restored for the next group."}, {"file": "corpus/train/train_0225_cwe787.cpp", "lines": "16-22", "code": "    unsigned char outbuf[4];
