    getNext()->write(outbuf, t);", "explanation": "t is derived directly from this->pos and used as the byte length passed to getNext()->write(outbuf, t), but outbuf is only 4 bytes. The pos==0 guard rules out the pos-1 unsigned underflow (pos>=1 so t>=0), so the residual hazard is the UPPER bound: if the append path ever lets pos exceed 5 (e.g. an off-by-one that permits pos==6), then t = pos-1 becomes 5 or more, and write() will read past the end of the 4-byte outbuf (out-of-bounds READ, CWE-125) and forward those extra bytes downstream, potentially overflowing the successor pipeline's destination (propagating to CWE-787). The invariant the implementation must uphold is 1 <= pos <= sizeof(inbuf) == 5, so that t is always in 0..4 and fits within outbuf."}, {"file": "corpus/train/train_0225_cwe787.cpp", "lines": "10-13", "code": "    for (int i = 0; i < 5; ++i)
    {
	lval *= 85;
	lval += (this->inbuf[i] - 33U);", "explanation": "The loop unconditionally consumes all 5 inbuf slots even on a partial flush where pos < 5. This is only correct if slots inbuf[pos..4] have been pre-padded with the digit 'u' (117); the repad on line 30 restores this AFTER a flush, but the FIRST flush of the object relies on the constructor (not shown) initialising inbuf to 117. If that initial padding invariant is ever broken, the loop reads stale/uninitialised bytes as base-85 digits (CWE-457/CWE-125 read of indeterminate data), producing wrong output — not a memory-safety break here since the read stays within the 5-byte array, but a correctness/data-integrity contract the constructor must uphold."}, {"file": "corpus/train/train_0225_cwe787.cpp", "lines": "13", "code": "	lval += (this->inbuf[i] - 33U);", "explanation": "Sign/range hygiene on the digit conversion: inbuf[i] is treated as a base-85 digit via inbuf[i] - 33U. Valid ASCII85 digit characters are '!'(33) .. 'u'(117), giving digit values 0..84. If the append path ever stores a byte < 33 into inbuf, the unsigned subtraction inbuf[i] - 33U underflows to a very large unsigned value (CWE-191), and lval*85 + that value yields a garbage 32-bit result; conversely a byte in 118..255 yields a digit > 84 so lval can exceed the 0..85^5-1 range the encoding guarantees. This is a decode-correctness defect, not a memory-safety one, but it shows flush() trusts the writer to have already rejected non-digit characters; the invariant is 'every byte in inbuf is in [33,117]'."}], "summary": "This is the fixed revision of qpdf's Pl_ASCII85Decoder::flush(). As shown, the loop bounds (i in 0..4 on a 5-byte inbuf, i in 3..0 on a 4-byte outbuf) are in-range, and the pos==0 guard prevents the pos-1 unsigned underflow, so flush() itself contains no directly-exploitable out-of-bounds access. Its memory safety is entirely contingent on the not-shown write()/append path enforcing 1 <= pos <= 5 and inbuf holding only valid base-85 digits; the labelled CWE-787 lives in that append path (an unbounded store into the fixed 5-byte inbuf), and the length t = pos-1 handed to a 4-byte outbuf is safe only while that invariant holds.", "reviewed_anchors": [{"anchor": "Pl_ASCII85Decoder::flush() signature (line 2)", "disposition": "dismissed", "reason": "No parameters/return; operates on member state only — surface is the members it touches, covered by the pos/inbuf anchors."}, {"anchor": "this->pos == 0 guard (line 4)", "disposition": "dismissed", "reason": "Correct guard; it is what prevents the pos-1 unsigned underflow, so it removes rather than creates a risk."}, {"anchor": "QTC::TC("libtests", ...) test hooks (lines 6, 24-25)", "disposition": "dismissed", "reason": "qpdf test-coverage instrumentation; no runtime data effect."}, {"anchor": "unsigned long lval accumulator (line 9)", "disposition": "dismissed", "reason": "Local accumulator; base-85 of 5 digits (max 85^5-1 = 4437053124) fits in unsigned long; only low 32 bits are used via the shift-out loop."}, {"anchor": "for (int i = 0; i < 5; ++i) reading this->inbuf[i] (lines 10-13)", "disposition": "finding", "reason": "Reads all 5 slots of the fixed inbuf on partial flush; relies on padding invariant and on the append path bounding inbuf — the central attack surface."}, {"anchor": "lval += (this->inbuf[i] - 33U) unsigned digit conversion (line 13)", "disposition": "finding", "reason": "Unsigned subtraction underflows if a byte < 33 was stored; trusts writer to have validated digit range."}, {"anchor": "unsigned char outbuf[4] fixed buffer (line 16)", "disposition": "finding", "reason": "Fixed 4-byte destination whose emitted length is the attacker-influenced t = pos-1; safe only if pos <= 5."}, {"anchor": "memset(outbuf, 0, 4) (line 17)", "disposition": "dismissed", "reason": "In-bounds zeroing of the 4-byte buffer; benign."}, {"anchor": "for (int i = 3; i >= 0; --i) outbuf[i] = lval & 0xff (lines 18-22)", "disposition": "dismissed", "reason": "Compi