{"subsystem": "GStreamer H.264 bitstream parser — the dec_ref_pic_marking() syntax element decoder inside the codecparsers library. gst_h264_slice_parse_dec_ref_pic_marking() decodes the "Decoded reference picture marking" section of an H.264 slice header (H.264/AVC spec section 7.3.3.3), populating a GstH264DecRefPicMarking substructure of the slice header with either IDR marking flags or a variable-length list of memory-management-control-operation (MMCO) commands.", "provenance": "Identified by the GStreamer naming conventions: the gst_h264_ prefix, GstH264SliceHdr / GstH264NalUnit / GstH264DecRefPicMarking / GstH264RefPicMarking typedefs, the NalReader bitstream reader and its READ_UINT8/READ_UE exp-Golomb macros, the GLib types guint/guint32 and the GST_DEBUG/GST_WARNING logging macros, and G_N_ELEMENTS. This is gsth264parser.c from gst-plugins-bad's gst/codecparsers. The banner comment "sample: primevul_c_train_2550_fixed" is an untrusted in-corpus label and was ignored; the code was reviewed blind on its merits.", "trust_boundary": "Fully untrusted. The NalReader (nr) wraps the raw RBSP bytes of an H.264 NAL unit that arrived from a network stream, container file, or capture device — entirely attacker-controllable. Every value pulled by READ_UINT8 and READ_UE (the flags, mem_mgmt_ctrl_op, and the per-command pic-num/frame-idx values) is decoded from that hostile bitstream. nalu->idr_pic_flag is likewise derived from the parsed NAL header. The write destination dec_ref_pic_m->ref_pic_marking[] is a FIXED-size array embedded in the caller-owned slice header, and the loop count is driven purely by attacker input, so this is a classic attacker-length-vs-fixed-buffer surface.", "what_the_code_does": [{"file": "corpus/train/train_0134_cwe787.c", "lines": "2-4", "code": "gst_h264_slice_parse_dec_ref_pic_marking (GstH264SliceHdr * slice,
