	    memcpy(data+i,af->badflag,SECTOR_SIZE);", "explanation": "Mirror of the previous issue in the normal tail. af->image_pagesize-SECTOR_SIZE (SECTOR_SIZE is a plain int) underflows/goes negative when SECTOR_SIZE > image_pagesize, and the comparison against the size_t counter i turns it into a huge bound, causing the memcpy to run off the end of data. Even without underflow, the loop and the memcpy are bounded only by image_pagesize/SECTOR_SIZE, not by the caller's buffer, so an oversized page relative to the buffer overflows it. The loop must be bounded by the trusted buffer capacity."}, {"file": "corpus/train/train_0182_cwe295.cpp", "lines": "87", "code": "res = uncompress(data,(uLongf *)bytes,compressed_data,compressed_data_len);", "explanation": "bytes is size_t* but is cast to uLongf* (unsigned long*). On LP64 these are the same width, but on LLP64 (Win64) unsigned long is 32-bit while size_t is 64-bit: uncompress would write a 32-bit length through a pointer the caller reads back as 64-bit, leaving the high half stale/garbage. That corrupted *bytes then feeds the sector-fill index arithmetic at lines 146/151, potentially producing an out-of-bounds write. Portability/type-punning defect; the destination length must be a real uLongf then assigned into *bytes."}, {"file": "corpus/train/train_0182_cwe295.cpp", "lines": "89-105", "code": "switch(res){
