	    case Z_STREAM_ERROR:
		(*af->error_reporter)("Z_STREAM_ERROR decompressing segment %" I64d,pagenum);", "explanation": "The zlib error switch omits break on every non-OK case, so a single error falls through and invokes every subsequent error_reporter call plus the default. This is a control-flow/logic defect (misleading multi-line error spew) rather than memory corruption, but if error_reporter is a fatal/longjmp handler the fall-through changes behaviour; the tag string "Z_ERRNOR" is also a typo. Low security impact but should be corrected with explicit breaks."}], "summary": "This AFFLIB page reader takes multiple attacker-controlled AFF-header/segment values (image_pagesize, image_sectorsize, the ALG_ZERO decoded length, the raw compressed bytes) and uses them as write sizes/indices into a caller buffer without bounding them against that buffer. The strongest issues are a controlled out-of-bounds heap write from the ALG_ZERO-supplied *bytes feeding the sector-fill loop (CWE-787), reliance on image_pagesize as the write size when it may exceed the caller's buffer, an unchecked malloc NULL deref, plus a 4-vs-8 byte OOB read, a divide-by-zero on zero sector size, and a compressed_data leak on the sanity-check early return. Overall: high-risk parser code for corrupt/malicious forensic images.", "reviewed_anchors": [{"anchor": "int af_get_page(AFFILE *af,int64_t pagenum,unsigned char *data,size_t *bytes)", "disposition": "finding", "reason": "*bytes is an in/out capacity and data an untrusted-size buffer; multiple writes ignore that capacity"}, {"anchor": "uint32_t arg / uint32_t pageflag", "disposition": "dismissed", "reason": "local flag holders; carry the attacker's algorithm selector but are only masked, no direct memory contract"}, {"anchor": "size_t page_len (malloc size, line 47)", "disposition": "finding", "reason": "attacker-controlled allocation size and buffer bound for the *(long*) read at line 82"}, {"anchor": "af_get_page_raw(af,pagenum,&arg,0,&page_len) return r", "disposit