rm's real bcopy, and private_key must be treated as read-only. If this codebase does not define its own memcpy-style bcopy macro (dst, src), this line is a wrong-buffer write to read-only key memory."}, {"file": "corpus/train/train_0077_cwe415.c", "lines": "69", "code": "    bcopy((uint8_t *) signature + curve->num_bytes, (uint8_t *) s, curve->num_bytes);", "explanation": "The same argument-order confusion appears in the output step. Under standard bcopy(src, dst, n) this copies FROM signature+curve->num_bytes INTO s — it reads the (uninitialized) upper half of the output buffer back into the s scratch words instead of writing the computed s out. The intended behaviour, per the non-native sibling uECC_vli_nativeToBytes(signature + num_bytes, num_bytes, s), is to store s INTO signature+num_bytes. With the reversed copy the second signature component is never emitted, so the returned signature's high half is left as whatever garbage was in the caller's buffer, producing an invalid signature and leaking prior buffer contents through it. The invariant: the s component must be written into the output, and the copy must respect bcopy's source-first ordering. This confirms the line-53 finding is a systematic bcopy(dst, src) vs bcopy(src, dst) mistake, not a one-off typo."}, {"file": "corpus/train/train_0077_cwe415.c", "lines": "13", "code": "    uECC_word_t *p = (uECC_word_t *)signature;", "explanation": "In the native-little-endian configuration the caller's byte buffer signature is reinterpreted as an array of uECC_word_t and then written through by EccPoint_mult using aligned word stores. Nothing guarantees signature is aligned to the platform's word (uECC_word_t) alignment — callers routinely pass byte buffers from packed structures or arbitrary offsets. On strict-alignment targets this is a misaligned access that faults or is silently miscompiled; even on lenient targets it is technically undefined behaviour (a strict-aliasing / alignment violation). The invariant: th