osition": "dismissed", "reason": "Size macros applied to trusted curve bit-counts; no attacker-controlled arithmetic."}], "findings": [{"title": "bcopy source/destination swapped writes into const private_key and drops the key load", "anchor": "bcopy((uint8_t *) tmp, private_key, BITS_TO_BYTES(curve->num_n_bits));", "file": "corpus/train/train_0077_cwe415.c", "line": "53", "code": "    bcopy((uint8_t *) tmp, private_key, BITS_TO_BYTES(curve->num_n_bits));", "bug_class": "Wrong-buffer write / function called with reversed arguments (write to read-only object)", "cwe": "CWE-787", "severity": "high", "where_it_lives": "corpus/train/train_0077_cwe415.c", "invariant": "The private_key parameter is const and must only be read; the intended operation is tmp := private_key. Any copy must use bcopy's real prototype bcopy(src, dst, n) so the destination is the second argument.", "failure_mode": "Standard bcopy(const void *src, void *dst, size_t n) treats the first argument as the source, so this call copies FROM tmp INTO private_key, writing BITS_TO_BYTES(num_n_bits) bytes over the caller's const private key buffer (undefined behaviour / secret-key corruption). Simultaneously tmp is never loaded with the private key d — it still holds the line-36/38 blinding value — so s = r*d at line 60 uses the wrong scalar and every emitted signature is invalid. Triggered on any native-little-endian build whenever the platform provides the real BSD bcopy rather than a memcpy-style (dst, src) macro.", "cve_analog": "", "what_to_confirm": "Whether this codebase defines a custom memcpy-style bcopy(dst, src, n) macro. If not, confirm the standard bcopy prototype is in scope, making line 53 a write into the const private_key and leaving tmp without d. The sibling non-native branch (line 55) shows the intended direction tmp := private_key."}, {"title": "bcopy source/destination swapped fails to emit the s signature component", "anchor": "bcopy((uint8_t *) signature + curve->num_bytes, (uint8_t *