    }", "explanation": "This is the core cryptographic defect. When source is anything other than RANDOM/URANDOM — and crucially when it is the DEFAULT value 0 (line 2) — the IV is filled from the C rand() PRNG. rand() is not a cryptographically secure generator: its internal state is small, it is usually seeded from low-entropy values (time, PID) that an attacker can guess or brute-force, and its output stream is fully determined by that seed. An attacker who can recover or guess the seed can reconstruct the entire IV. A predictable IV defeats the security of the cipher that consumes it (e.g., enabling chosen-plaintext/known-IV attacks against CBC/CTR modes, or breaking IV-uniqueness assumptions), even when the key stays secret. Because the weak path is the DEFAULT, the most common call form mcrypt_create_iv($size) silently gets predictable IVs. The invariant: an IV intended for cryptographic use MUST come from a CSPRNG / kernel entropy source, never from rand(); ideally the weak source should not be selectable at all, and certainly must not be the default. Secondary, minor artifact: 255.0 * rand() / RAND_MAX yields a non-uniform byte distribution (value 255 occurs only for rand()==RAND_MAX, and floating truncation biases the low bytes), but this is dwarfed by the predictability problem."}, {"file": "corpus/train/train_0262_cwe310.cpp", "lines": "10", "code": "  char *iv = (char*)calloc(size + 1, 1);", "explanation": "The calloc return value is used without a NULL check. On allocation failure (which an attacker can push toward by requesting a very large size — up to nearly INT_MAX bytes, since the only cap is size < INT_MAX on line 3), calloc returns NULL. The code then dereferences iv unconditionally: in the device branch read(fd, iv + read_bytes, ...) writes into NULL+offset, and in the rand branch iv[--size] = ... writes through a NULL pointer. Either is a NULL-pointer dereference / wild write that crashes the HHVM process (denial of service). The invariant: every malloc/calloc/realloc result must be NULL-checked before use, and on failure the function must clean up and return false (as it already does for the open() and short-read failures)."}, {"file": "corpus/train/train_0262_cwe310.cpp", "lines": "19-21", "code": "    for (read_bytes = 0; read_bytes < size && n >= 0; read_bytes += n) {
      n = read(fd, iv + read_bytes, size - read_bytes);
    }", "explanation": "The loop termination depends on read() either filling the buffer or returning a negative error. It does NOT handle read() returning 0. read() returns 0 to signal end-of-file / no more data; for /dev/random this normally does not happen (it blocks instead), but if the descriptor's behavior differs (e.g., the device is exhausted-and-closed semantics on some platforms, a restricted/emulated environment, or a race that yields EOF), n becomes 0, read_bytes stops advancing, and the guard n >= 0 remains true — an infinite loop that hangs the request thread and burns CPU (denial of service). The invariant: a read loop must treat a 0-byte read as a terminal condition (break and report insufficient data), not merely as "non-negative, keep going." The impact is bounded compared with the crypto defect but is a genuine latent hang."}], "summary": "The dominant issue is cryptographic: the default source (0) routes IV generation through the non-cryptographic C rand() PRNG (lines 29-33), producing predictable initialization vectors and undermining any cipher that uses them (CWE-330). Secondary defects are an unchecked calloc return that becomes a NULL-pointer write on large-size allocation failure (CWE-476, line 10) and a read loop that can hang on a 0-byte read (CWE-835, lines 19-21). The size validation and device-path completeness checks are correct.", "reviewed_anchors": [{"anchor": "HHVM_FUNCTION(mcrypt_create_iv, int size, int source /* = 0 */) — signature and default source=0 (line 2)", "disposition": "finding", "reason": "Default source value 0 does not match RANDOM/URANDOM and therefore routes the common call form to the weak rand() branch."}, {"anchor": "int size parameter (line 2)", "disposition": "dismissed", "reason": "Caller-controlled length but properly bounded to (0, INT_MAX) at lines 3-7; no overflow or under-allocation results."}, {"anchor": "int source selector parameter (line 2)", "disposition": "finding", "reason": "Selects the entropy 