{"subsystem": "ZNC IRC-bouncer DCC module. This is the CTCP DCC handler (an OnPrivCTCP module hook) that intercepts DCC CHAT/SEND/RESUME/ACCEPT negotiation messages received from a remote IRC peer and sets up / rewrites a DCC "bounce" so that file transfers and chats between two IRC clients are relayed through the ZNC process. It parses the attacker-supplied CTCP payload, allocates local bounce listeners via CDCCBounce::DCCRequest, and forwards rewritten DCC handshake lines to the locally attached user.", "provenance": "Identified by the ZNC-specific API surface: the module hook signature EModRet OnPrivCTCP(CNick&, CString&) with return values HALTCORE/CONTINUE, ZNC string type CString with .Token()/.Equals()/.ToULong()/.ToUShort() helpers, the CNick/CDCCBounce/CSocket classes, the m_pUser/m_pClient CUser/CClient members, PutUser(), BeginSockets()/EndSockets(), and CUtils::GetIP/GetLongIP. The header comment '/* sample: primevul_train_3545_vuln */' and the file name train_0246_cwe399.cpp mark it as a PrimeVul training sample tagged CWE-399 (resource management). This is the DCC bounce logic from ZNC's modules/dcc.cpp.", "trust_boundary": "The trust boundary is the IRC network. OnPrivCTCP is invoked with Nick (the remote sender) and sMessage (the raw CTCP payload) both sourced directly from a private CTCP message sent by ANOTHER IRC user to the ZNC-hosted user. Every token in sMessage is fully attacker-controlled: the DCC sub-command (Token(1)), the file name (Token(2)), the peer IP as a packed unsigned long (Token(3)), the peer port (Token(4)), the file size (Token(5)). Nick.GetNickMask()/GetNick() are also attacker-influenced and spoofable. Nothing here is authenticated; the sender need not be on the user's contact list. The parsed IP/port are later used to open outbound connections, and the raw file name / trailing tokens are echoed back into the user's IRC stream.", "what_the_code_does": [{"file": "corpus/train/train_0246_cwe399.cpp", "lines": "2", "code": "	virtual EModRet OnPrivCTCP(CNick& Nick, CString& sMessage) {", "explanation": "This is a ZNC module callback. OnPrivCTCP is fired by the core whenever the attached user receives a private (non-channel) CTCP message. Nick is the remote sender's identity object and sMessage is the decoded CTCP payload (the bytes between the \001 delimiters). Returning EModRet HALTCORE tells the core to swallow the message (the module has handled it) while CONTINUE lets normal processing proceed. Both parameters are non-const references originating from the wire, so this method is a raw parser of untrusted remote input."}, {"file": "corpus/train/train_0246_cwe399.cpp", "lines": "3", "code": "		if (sMessage.Equals("DCC ", false, 4) && m_pUser->IsUserAttached()) {", "explanation": "The single gate before any DCC handling. sMessage.Equals("DCC ", false, 4) does a case-insensitive (false = not case-sensitive) comparison of the first 4 characters against the literal 'DCC '. m_pUser->IsUserAttached() requires that the ZNC user currently has an IRC client connected (otherwise there is nobody to bounce to). If either is false the method falls through to the CONTINUE at line 52. Note this only checks the prefix; the remainder of the payload is unvalidated at this point."}, {"file": "corpus/train/train_0246_cwe399.cpp", "lines": "5-9", "code": "			CString sType = sMessage.Token(1);
			CString sFile = sMessage.Token(2);
			unsigned long uLongIP = sMessage.Token(3).ToULong();
			unsigned short uPort = sMessage.Token(4).ToUShort();
			unsigned long uFileSize = sMessage.Token(5).ToULong();", "explanation": "The payload is split on spaces into tokens. Token(0) is 'DCC'; Token(1) is the DCC sub-command (CHAT/SEND/RESUME/ACCEPT); Token(2) is the file name; Token(3) is the peer's IPv4 address encoded as a 32-bit decimal integer (classic DCC on-wire IP form) converted with ToULong(); Token(4) is the peer's TCP port converted with ToUShort(); Token(5) is the advertised file size. ToULong()/ToUShort() are ZNC helpers that parse a numeric string and silently yield 0 on failure or on empty tokens, so every one of these five values is attacker-chosen and none is range-validated here. sFile in particular is retained verbatim for later re-emission."}, {"file": "corpus/train/train_0246_cwe399.cpp", "lines": "11-13", "code": "			if (sType.Equals("CHAT")) {
				CNick FromNick(Nick.GetNickMask());
				unsigned short uBNCPort = CDCCBounce::DCCRequest(FromNick.GetNick(), uLongIP, uPort, "", true, this, CUtils::GetIP(uLongIP));", "explanation": "The CHAT branch. It constructs a fresh CNick from the sender's full nick!user@host mask, then calls the static CDCCBounce::DCCRequest to allocate a bounce endpoint. The arguments are the sender nick, the attacker-supplied uLongIP and uPort (the remote peer the bounce will ultimately talk to), an empty file name, a boolean true (this is a chat, not a file send), 'this' module pointer, and a human-readable IP string derived from uLongIP via CUtils::GetIP. DCCRequest opens a local listening socket (a CDCCBounce) and returns the local port it bound to (0 on failure). Every DCC CHAT thus causes a new socket/port to be allocated on the ZNC host."}, {"file": "corpus/train/train_0246_cwe399.cpp", "lines": "14-17", "code": "				if (uBNCPort) {
					CString sIP = GetLocalDCCIP();
					m_pUser->PutUser(":" + Nick.GetNickMask() + " PRIVMSG " + m_pUser->GetNick() + " :\001DCC CHAT chat " + CString(CUtils::GetLongIP(sIP)) + " " + CString(uBNCPort) + "\001");
