 on the number of simultaneous bounces, and no timeout visible here. A hostile peer (or many) can flood the user with DCC CHAT/SEND CTCPs and force ZNC to exhaust file descriptors, ephemeral ports, and memory (each pending bounce holds a socket until it times out or the user connects). This denial-of-service via unbounded object creation is the core CWE-399/CWE-400 concern: the implementation must bound the number and lifetime of outstanding bounce listeners."}, {"file": "corpus/train/train_0246_cwe399.cpp", "lines": "7-8", "code": "			unsigned long uLongIP = sMessage.Token(3).ToULong();
			unsigned short uPort = sMessage.Token(4).ToUShort();", "explanation": "Attacker-directed outbound connection (SSRF / open relay). uLongIP and uPort come straight from the remote peer's CTCP tokens and are handed to DCCRequest as the destination the bounce will ultimately connect to. The remote peer can therefore point the bounce at any address, including loopback (127.0.0.1) or an RFC1918 host reachable from the ZNC machine and any port (e.g. an internal SSH/HTTP/admin service). Combined with the fact that the sender is unauthenticated, ZNC becomes a relay to internal services once the user's client connects to the bounce. The implementation should refuse non-routable / internal destinations and validate that the advertised IP matches the sender before opening the outbound leg (CWE-918)."}, {"file": "corpus/train/train_0246_cwe399.cpp", "lines": "23", "code": "					m_pUser->PutUser(":" + Nick.GetNickMask() + " PRIVMSG " + m_pUser->GetNick() + " :\001DCC SEND " + sFile + " " + CString(CUtils::GetLongIP(sIP)) + " " + CString(uBNCPort) + " " + CString(uFileSize) + "\001");", "explanation": "Unsanitised reflection of attacker data into the user's IRC stream (also lines 16, 34, 44). sFile (Token(2)) and the raw echoed tokens are concatenated straight into a PRIVMSG that PutUser writes to the attached client. Although space-tokenisation prevents embedded spaces, the file name can still contain a stray \001 that prematurely closes / re-opens the CTCP frame, letting the peer inject an extra CTCP or spoof additional DCC parameters interpreted by the victim's client. The Nick.GetNickMask() prefix is likewise attacker-influenced and spoofable, so the forwarded line can impersonate arbitrary senders to the client. The implementation must strip control bytes (\001, and defensively CR/LF) from sFile and the echoed tokens before re-emission (CWE-150 / CWE-93)."}, {"file": "corpus/train/train_0246_cwe399.cpp", "lines": "33", "code": "					if (pSock->GetLocalPort() == uResumePort) {", "explanation": "Weak connection lookup keyed only on an attacker-supplied port. RESUME/ACCEPT match a bounce purely by a 16-bit port number taken from the peer's own token (uResumePort / Token(3)), with no check that the matched CDCCBounce actually belongs to a transfer with THIS sender. A malicious peer who can guess or brute-force the small port space (at most 65535 values, realistically a handful of active bounces) can address another user's in-flight transfer, causing RESUME/ACCEPT rewrites to be forwarded for a connection they do not own — a cross-session confusion/information-disclosure of the other transfer's GetUserPort()/GetLocalPort(). The implementation should scope the socket search to bounces owned by the requesting nick."}, {"file": "corpus/train/train_0246_cwe399.cpp", "lines": "3", "code": "			if (sMessage.Equals("DCC ", false, 4) && m_pUser->IsUserAttached()) {", "explanation": "Insufficient input validation of the payload shape. The only gate is the 4-char 'DCC ' prefix; the code then assumes well-formed tokens. Missing tokens make ToULong/ToUShort return 0, so a bare 'DCC SEND' with no IP/port still drives DCCRequest with uLongIP=0/uPort=0 (allocating a bounce toward 0.0.0.0:0), and an unrecognised sub-command still returns HALTCORE, silently discarding what the user might have needed to see. Robust handling requires validating token count and numeric ranges before acting (CWE-20)."}], "summary": "This is ZNC's DCC-bounce CTCP handler, a raw parser of unauthenticated remote IRC CTCP payloads. The tagged resource-management issue is real: RESUME/ACCEPT blindly C-style-cast every module socket to CDCCBounce* (type confusion, CWE-843) and every CHAT/SEND allocates an unbounded, unthrottled bounce listener (DoS, CWE-400/399). Beyond that, attacker-supplied IP/port drive outbound connections (SSRF), and attacker file names are reflected unsanitised into the user's IRC stream (CTCP injection). All findings are latent in the shown handler but their full impact depends on CDCCBounce::DCCRequest and the socket-set contents, which are not provided.", "reviewed_anchors": [{"anchor": "virtual EModRet OnPrivCTCP(CNick& Nick, CString& sMessage) (line 2)", "disposition": "finding", "reason": "Entry point taking fully attacker-controlled remote CTCP payload; root of the untrusted data flow."}, {"anchor": "sMessage.Equals("DCC ", false, 4) && m_pUser->IsUserAttached() (line 3)", "disposition": "finding", "reason": "Only validation gate; a 4-char prefix check that admits malformed/short payloads."}, {"anchor": "sType = sMessage.Token(1) (line 5)", "disposition": "dismissed", "reason": "Sub-command selector compared against fixed literals; no buffer or arithmetic contract of its own."}, {"anchor": "sFile = sMessage.Token(2) (line 6)", "disposition": "finding", "reason": "Attacker file name reflected verbatim into outbound IRC/CTCP lines without sanitisation."}, {"anchor": "uLongIP = sMessage.Token(3).ToULong() (line 7)", "disposition": "finding", "reason": "Attacker-controlled destination IP passed to DCCRequest (SSRF)."}, {"anchor": "uPort = sMessage.Token(4).ToUShort() (line 8)", "disposition": "finding", "reason": "Attacker-controlled destination port paired with uLongIP for the outbound bounce leg (SSRF)."}, {"anchor": "uFileSize = sMessage.Token(5).ToULong() (line 9)", "disposition": "dismissed", "reason": "Only echoed back to the user as a size field; no buffer sizing or allocation is driven by it here."}, {"anchor": "CDCCBounce::DCCRequest(...) CHAT (line 13)", "disposition": "finding", "reason": "Allocates an unbounded bounce listener per request and initiates an attacker-directed connection."}, {"anchor": "CDCCBounce::DCCRequest(...) SEND (line 20)", "disposition": "finding", "reason": "Same unbounded-allocation / SSRF contract as the CHAT variant; covered by the same findings."}, {"anchor": "m_pUser->PutUser(...) (lines 16, 23, 34, 44)", "disposition": "finding", "reason": "Reflects attacker-controlled sFile/tokens and spoofable nick mask into the client's IRC stream with \001 framing (CTCP injection)."}, {"anchor": "uResumePort = sMessage.Token(3).ToUShort() (line 27)", "disposition": "finding", "reason": "Attacker-chosen 16-bit key used as the sole selector for another connection in the RESUME lookup."}, {"anchor": "for (it = BeginSockets(); it != EndSockets(); ++it) (lines 30, 40)", "disposition": "finding", "reason": "Iterates the entire module socket set feeding the unchecked downcast; scope not restricted to the sender's own bounces."}, {"anchor": "CDCCBounce* pSock = (CDCCBounce*) *it (lines 31, 41)", "disposition": "finding", "reason": "Unchecked C-style downcast then dereference — type confusion if the set holds any non-CDCCBounce socket."}, {"anchor": "pSock->GetLocalPort()/GetUserPort() comparisons (lines 33, 43)", "disposition": "finding", "reason": "Reads through the mis-cast pointer and matches on an attacker-supplied port; part of the type-confusion and weak-lookup findings."}, {"anchor": "return HALTCORE (line 49)", "disposition": "dismissed", "reason": "Control-flow result; swallowing the CTCP after a prefix match is a minor UX/logic concern, not a memory-safety contract."}, {"anchor": "return CONTINUE (line 52)", "disposition": "dismissed", "reason": "Default pass-through when the DCC prefix does not match; no security contract."}], "findings": [{"title": "Unchecked downcast of arbitrary CSocket* to CDCCBounce* (type confusion)", "anchor": "CDCCBounce* pSock = (CDCCBounce*) *it;", "file": "corpus/train/train_0246_cwe399.cpp", "line": "31", "code": "					CDCCBounce* pSock = (CDCCBounce*) *it;", "bug_class": "Type confusion via unchecked C-style downcast (out-of-bounds read through mis-typed pointer)", "cwe": "CWE-843", "severity": "high", "where_it_lives": "corpus/train/train_0246_cwe399.cpp (RESUME line 31 and ACCEPT line 41); depends on the socket set populated by CDCCBounce/DCCRequest in implementation (file not provided)", "invariant": "Every socket r